Task 1 - Introduction¶

1.1 Phase 1 Summary¶

In Phase 1, we focused on preparing a clean and structured dataset to enable predictive modeling in Phase 2. The dataset captured key aspects of Indian e-commerce grocery deliveries, including platform used, delivery time, order value, service rating, product category, customer feedback, and refund request status. The target variable was Refund Requested, a binary indicator denoting whether a customer sought a refund.

Key tasks performed:

  • Data Cleaning & Preprocessing: Removed ID-like fields (e.g., Order ID, Customer ID), handled missing values, converted time-related fields into numerical format, encoded binary/categorical variables, and treated outliers using percentile clamping.
  • Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA): Conducted univariate, bivariate, and multivariate visual analysis. Key insights included high refund rates in categories like Personal Care and Snacks & Beverages, a high refund count on platforms like Swiggy Instamart, and surprisingly frequent refund requests despite high service ratings.
  • Visualization: Created 11 insightful visual plots, including correlation heatmaps and categorical breakdowns by platform and product.

These efforts established the groundwork for supervised learning models to be built in Phase 2, where we aim to predict refund behavior and uncover feature importance using classification algorithms.

1.2 Report Overview¶

This Phase 2 report presents a comprehensive predictive modeling pipeline applied to an e-commerce refund prediction dataset. Building on the data preprocessing and exploratory analysis completed in Phase 1, this report applies advanced machine learning techniques including feature selection, model training, hyperparameter tuning, and evaluation using various classifiers. Four models—Logistic Regression, Decision Tree, Support Vector Machine (SVM), and k-Nearest Neighbors (KNN)—are rigorously tested and fine-tuned using GridSearchCV, with their performance visualized through confusion matrices and hyperparameter tuning plots. Additionally, a sentiment analysis component is introduced to enhance interpretability, offering a business-focused justification for the high classification accuracy observed.

The report includes all necessary stages of a robust machine learning workflow: preprocessing pipelines, feature selection using SelectKBest, cross-validation, model tuning, evaluation using classification metrics, and visual analysis. It concludes with model comparisons and a critical reflection on the strengths and limitations of the chosen methods, providing insights into the business implications of the results.

1.3 Overview of Methodology¶

The predictive modeling methodology adopted in this project follows a structured machine learning pipeline, beginning with data preprocessing and culminating in evaluation and model comparison. After completing Phase 1 tasks, which involved data cleaning and exploration, Phase 2 focused on constructing, tuning, and evaluating classification models to predict whether a customer would request a refund.

The process began with the integration of a sentiment analysis component using the TextBlob library, which transformed free-text customer feedback into a numerical Sentiment score. This enriched the feature set with an interpretable variable highly indicative of customer dissatisfaction. Non-numeric categorical variables were encoded using one-hot encoding, while numerical features were passed through untransformed. A ColumnTransformer and Pipeline were used to organize this transformation and ensure consistent preprocessing across training and testing splits.

Feature selection was conducted using SelectKBest with the f_classif scoring function to retain the top 10 most relevant features. The data was then split into training and test sets (80/20), and numerical features were scaled using StandardScaler to ensure fair distance-based computations, particularly for the KNN and SVM models.

Four supervised classification algorithms were implemented:

  • Logistic Regression for its interpretability and performance on linearly separable data,
  • Decision Tree for its ability to handle complex feature interactions and rank feature importance,
  • Support Vector Machine (SVM) for optimal margin separation,
  • K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN) for its simplicity and proximity-based decision-making.

Each model underwent hyperparameter tuning via GridSearchCV with 5-fold cross-validation to optimize performance. The best-performing parameters were selected, and final predictions were evaluated using classification reports and confusion matrices. Additional evaluation was supported by tuning visualizations and a final comparison table. Together, these steps ensured a rigorous, transparent, and reproducible modeling approach with strong business relevance.

Task 2 - Predictive Modelling¶

2.1 Feature Selection¶

To identify the most relevant features for predicting refund requests in Indian e-commerce deliveries, we applied a univariate statistical feature selection method: ANOVA F-test (f_classif). This method evaluates the relationship between each feature and the binary target variable (Refund Requested) by computing the F-score for each input feature. The higher the F-score, the more likely the feature is to be useful for classification.

Before applying, feature selection:

  • The target variable 'Refund Requested' was already binary encoded (0=No Refund, 1=Refund) in the cleaned dataset from Phase1, so no additional encoding (eg., LabelEncoder) was required.
  • Converted categorical predictors to numeric format via one-hot encoding using 'pd.get_dummies'.

We selected the Top 10 features based on the highest F-scores using SelectKBest. The selected features represent those most statistically associated with the likelihood of a refund, forming a compact yet informative subset for subsequent predictive modeling.

Feature selection was performed on the full dataset without platform-wise segmentation,as the goal was to identify important predictors of refund behaviour across all e-commerce platforms.

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Interpretation: The bar chart shows the top 10 features selected by ANOVA F-test (f_classif). It highlights that Service Rating is the most important predictor of refund requests. In addition, specific types of customer feedback such as complaints about wrong items, packaging, delivery issues show moderate predictive power. These findings support the hypothesis that customer dissatisfaction - particularly quantified by low service ratings and negative feedback - plays a critical role in refund likelihood.

The F-Score (from ANOVA) measures how well each feature distinguishes between classes by comparing the variance between and within groups. A higher F-score indicates that the feature has a stronger statistical relationship with the target and is more useful for classification

a) Algorithm - Logistic Regression¶

In [17]:
#Train-Test Split
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X_new_df, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=999)

#Logistic Regression with GridSearchCV
log_reg = LogisticRegression(solver='liblinear', random_state=999)
param_grid = {
    'C': [0.01,0.1,1,10,100],
    'penalty': ['l1', 'l2']
}

grid_search = GridSearchCV(log_reg, param_grid, cv=5, scoring='accuracy')
grid_search.fit(X_train, y_train)


#Best Model and Parameters
best_model = grid_search.best_estimator_
print("Best Parameters:", grid_search.best_params_)
print("Best Cross-Validation Accuracy:", grid_search.best_score_)    

Best Parameters: {'C': 0.01, 'penalty': 'l1'}
Best Cross-Validation Accuracy: 1.0

Interpretation: We used GridSearchCV to tune the logistic regression model over a grid of 5 regularization strengths(C=0.01,0.1,1,10,100) and 2 penalty types. The solver 'liblinear' was chosen as it supports both l1 (Lasso) and l2 (Ridge) penalties. The objective was to identify the optimal balance between model complexity and generalization.

C=0.01 means strong regularization (simpler model, less overfitting) and C=100 means weak regularization (flexible model, risk of overfitting). l1 encourages sparsity by setting some coefficients to zero, effectively performing feature selection. l2 shrinks all coefficients without eliminating any, helping to stabilize the model.

A standard 80/20 train-test split was used to ensure sufficient training data while retaining a representative test set for final evaluation. With 5000 rows, this approach provides both robustness and reliability in performance estimation.

Business Insight¶

Logistic Regression stood out not just for its perfect accuracy, but for its interpretability - an essential trait in real-world business applications. This model provides clear, linear relationships between inputs and the likelihood of a refund, making it easy for non-technical stakeholders to understand how each factor contributes to the outcome. For eg., negative sentiment in customer feedback or low service ratings directly increase the predicted probability of a refund. These insights can be embedded into operational systems, allowing customer service teams to flag at-risk orders or trigger personalized follow-up actions. Because it is lightweight and fast, logistic regression is especially suitable for deployment in real-time environments where quick, explainable decisions matter.

b) Algorithm - Decision Tree¶

In [21]:
#Train-Test Split
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X_new_df, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=999)

#Decision Tree with GridSearchCV
tree = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=999)
param_grid_tree = {
    'max_depth': [2,4,6,8,10],
    'min_samples_split': [2,5,10],
    'criterion': ['gini', 'entropy']
}

grid_search_tree = GridSearchCV(tree, param_grid_tree, cv=5, scoring='accuracy')
grid_search_tree.fit(X_train, y_train)


#Best Model results
best_tree = grid_search_tree.best_estimator_
print("Best Parameters:", grid_search_tree.best_params_)
print("Best Cross-Validation Accuracy:", grid_search_tree.best_score_)    

Best Parameters: {'criterion': 'gini', 'max_depth': 2, 'min_samples_split': 2}
Best Cross-Validation Accuracy: 1.0

Interpretation: The Decision Tree Classifier achieved perfect cross-validation accuracy (1.0) with a very shallow tree (max_depth=2) using the 'gini' impurity criterion. This indicates that a small number of features (like 'Service Rating' and 'Customer Feedback') were highly effective in seperating the target classes. The optimal value of min_samples_split=2 allowed the model fully utilize these clear patterns.

The Decision Tree was tuned over a range of max_depth (2 to 10) to balance underfitting and overfitting.The min_samples_split parameter was varied to control tree complexity and both gini (faster, default) and entropy criteria (based on information gain, slightly more computationally expensive) were tested to identify the most informative splits. These choices are well-suited to the structure and size of the dataset.

A standard 80/20 train-test split was used to ensure sufficient training data while retaining a representative test set for final evaluation. With 5000 rows, this approach provides both robustness and reliability in performance estimation.

Business Insight¶

The Decision Tree model mirrors how many customer service policies are already structured-through simple, interpretable "if-then" rules. This makes it a natural fit for frontline teams and quality assurance managers who need clarity and confidence in automated decisions. In our case, even a shallow tree (with a max depth of just 2) was able to perfectly classify refund requests using a few critical features like service rating and specific feedback categories. This simplicity is a strength - it means that complex predictive systems can be boiled down into straightforward guidelines like "flag all orders with poor ratings and negative sentiment." Such transparency allows for seamless integration into business workflows, where trust in automated decisions is just as important as accuracy.

In practice, this can enable real-time refund risk scoring based on proximity to known refund-prone transactions, assisting customer service agents in prioritizing actions and enabling automated alerts for potential service issues.

#Train test split

    'hidden_layer_sizes': [(64,32), (128,64)],
    'activation': ['relu', 'tanh'],
    'learning_rate_init': [0.001, 0.01],
    'alpha': [0.0001, 0.001], #L2 regularization

}

    scoring='accuracy',
    verbose=2,

Interpretation: To enhance the predictive capabilities of our refund classification model, we implemented a feedforward neural network using the MLPClassifier from scikit-learn library. This model type, known as Multi-Layer Perceptron (MLP), supports gradient based optimization, backpropogation and mini-batch training, making it well-suited for learning complex, non-linear relationships.

The classification task - determining whether a customer will request a refund - involved structured features derived from service rating and customer feedback. Our neural network architecture was configured with two hidden layers, tested with both (64,32) and (128,64) neuron configuartions. The input layer accepted 10 neurons corresponding to the most important features selected via feature selection. The final output layer used a single neuron for binary classification, with internal use of a sigmoid-like activation.

To train the model, we adopted a mini-batch stochastic gradient descent approach via the adam solver, which combines the benefits of RMSProp and momentum to adaptively adjust learning rates. each training epoch represented one complete pass through the dataset. We set max_iter = 200 to allow sufficient convergence time. During each epoch, the model performed a forward pass to generate predictions, followed by backpropogation to compute gradients of the loss function with respect to the weights. These gradients were then used to update the weights in a direction that minimized binary cross-entropy loss. This iterative process allowed model to gradually learn the optimal decision boundary seperating refund from non-refund classes.

We tuned six key hyperparameters using GridSearchCV:

  1. hidden_layer_sizes: Compared two-layer architectures (64,32) and (128,64)
  2. activation: ReLU and Tanh were evaluated for non-linear transformation
  3. learning_rate_init: Two values tested - 0.001 and 0.01
  4. alpha: L2 regularization values 0.0001 and 0.001 were used to reduce overfitting
  5. batch_size: 32 and 64 were evaluated to control update frequency
  6. max_iter: Fixed at 200 to ensure convergence during tuning

Grid search was conducted using 3-fold cross-validation for performance and runtime efficiency, generating a total of 64 parameter combinations. Although 5-fold cross-validation istypically preferred for better generalization estimates, a 3-fold CV provided a reasonable trade-off between evaluation depth and computational feasibility, given the model complexity and number of configurations.

The best model returned following parameters: activation: ReLU, hidden_layer_sizes: (64,32), learning_rate_init: 0.001, alpha: 0.0001, batch_size:32 max_iter:200. When evaluated on the test set, the model achieved 100% accuracy, precision, recall and F1-score, indicating perfect classification performance. While such results are rare, in this context they were validated by the structured and high-signal nature of the dataset, especially the clear influence of service rating and sentiment linked to customer feedback.

To interpret the tuning process, we created five plots: Activation Function Vs Accuracy showed negligible performance differences between ReLU and Tanh, but ReLU was preferred for its faster convergence. Learning Rate Vs Accuracy indicated both tested rates achieved near-perfect accuracy, though 0.001 was was slightly more stable. Batch Size Vs Accuracy showed batch size 32 marginally outperformed 64, confirming that more frequent weights aided convergence. Regularization (Alpha) Vs Accuracy revealed both regularization values resulted in perfect accuracy, with 0.0001 chosen to avoid unnecessary penalization. Hidden Layer Size Vs Axxuracy demonstrated that both network configurations yielded similar results, but the simpler (64,32) was selected to reduce computational load and overfitting potential.

In conclusion, the neural network successfully learned to classify refund requests with perfect accuracy, supported by clean feature signals and robust, consistent tuning. This task demonstrated how MLPs, even without deep learning libraries like TensorFlow, can provide high-performance models when paired with strong, scalable data preprocessing, highly relevant features, and careful hyperparameter optimization. The model's success was further reinforced trhough the stability of tuning results and the consistency of performance across parameter choices.

Justification: Sentiment Analysis Visual Insights¶

Visual 1: Distribution of Sentiment Scores¶

This histogram gives us a sense of how customers are feeling in general, based on their feedback. What’s immediately noticeable is that opinions aren’t just scattered randomly they are very polarized. Most customers either feel very positive or quite negative about their experience, with fewer in the neutral zone.

This kind of strong split is helpful for our models. When customers are this clearly divided in their sentiment, it's much easier for algorithms to separate refund from non-refund cases. In other words, the model doesn’t have to guess much — the sentiment already does a lot of the work.

Visual 2: Boxplot of Sentiment vs Refund Status¶

Here, we’ve broken down sentiment by whether or not a customer requested a refund. The result is striking: people who asked for a refund had consistently lower (more negative) sentiment, while those who didn’t had noticeably higher (positive) sentiment.

This boxplot is our strongest visual proof that sentiment is a powerful predictor. It shows that sentiment can almost act like a boundary — customers fall on one side or the other depending on whether they’re happy or unhappy. This helps explain why even simple models like Logistic Regression or KNN are performing so well — the data practically separates itself.

Visual 3: Mean Sentiment by Platform¶

This plot compares the average customer sentiment across different e-commerce platforms. While all platforms have a generally positive tilt, some — like Jiomart — clearly have more satisfied customers than others.

These platform-level differences can help models pick up patterns. For example, if one platform consistently has higher satisfaction, the model might weigh refund likelihood differently depending on where the order came from. Models like Random Forest or Decision Trees are especially good at capturing this kind of relationship.

Together, these visualizations reveal that sentiment is not just an added feature it is central to understanding refund behavior. Whether through overall distribution, direct correlation with refunds, or platform-level patterns, sentiment offers strong, intuitive signals that our models are clearly picking up on.

Task 3: Critique & Limitations¶

Despite the perfect classification performance achieved by all four machine learning models (Logistic Regression, Decision Tree, SVM, and KNN), it is important to critically evaluate the reliability and generalizability of these results. While such high accuracy is ideal, it also raises the need to investigate potential issues such as data leakage, overfitting, or excessive feature-target correlation.

One major factor contributing to the perfect scores is the presence of highly predictive features, particularly the Sentiment score derived from customer feedback, and Service Rating. As confirmed by multiple visualizations (e.g., boxplots and histograms), these features exhibit a strong separation between refund and non-refund cases, making the classification task relatively straightforward. Although this strengthens model performance, it also implies that the models may be heavily reliant on sentiment polarity, which could limit their adaptability to future datasets where textual data is unavailable or varies in tone due to cultural or linguistic changes.

Additionally, the dataset used is clean, well-balanced, and free of noise, which may not represent real-world data distributions. In production environments, data is often messier, with missing values, ambiguous feedback, or mislabeled entries. The models were trained and validated on a static dataset using an 80/20 split, which might not reflect evolving customer behavior or seasonal patterns that affect refund likelihood.

From a modeling perspective, while hyperparameter tuning was conducted using GridSearchCV with cross-validation, no external validation (e.g., using a completely unseen holdout dataset) was applied. This limits the ability to measure true generalization performance. Moreover, since all models produced identical accuracy (100%), paired t-tests for comparison were not meaningful, and model selection was instead based on interpretability and practical deployment considerations.ROC curves and AUC scores were not included as all models achieved perfect classification (100% accuracy, precision and recall). In such cases, the ROC curve would show a trivial top-left corner trace with AUC=1.0, offering no additional insight.

Finally, the reliance on engineered features like sentiment assumes access to detailed customer feedback. In real-world applications, such textual data may be unavailable, inconsistent, or deliberately manipulated. If sentiment scoring is removed or altered, the performance of the current models may degrade significantly.

Task 4: Summary & Conclusions¶

4.1 Project Summary¶

This project focused on building a robust classification system to predict whether an e-commerce customer would request a refund. In Phase 1, we conducted data cleaning, removed ID-like variables, transformed categorical data, and performed detailed exploratory visualizations. These steps uncovered strong patterns between features such as delivery delay, service rating, and refund behavior.

In Phase 2, we enhanced the dataset by engineering a new Sentiment feature derived from customer feedback using TextBlob. This polarity score was a strong indicator of customer dissatisfaction and significantly improved model separability. We implemented four machine learning algorithms: Logistic Regression, Decision Tree, Support Vector Machine (SVM), and K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN). Each model was tuned using GridSearchCV with 5-fold cross-validation. All models achieved perfect classification scores (100% accuracy, precision, recall, and F1-score). Performance was validated using confusion matrices and tuning visualizations. A final comparison table summarized their predictive effectiveness.

4.2 Summary of Findings¶

  • The Sentiment feature proved to be one of the strongest predictors of refund behavior, as confirmed by statistical performance and visual insights.
  • All four classifiers achieved perfect predictive performance, largely due to the clear separability introduced by sentiment and service-related features.
  • SVM and Logistic Regression benefitted from linear decision boundaries, while Decision Tree and KNN captured interaction and distance-based trends effectively.
  • Hyperparameter tuning visualizations confirmed that model performance was robust across various configurations, with little sensitivity to changes in kernel, neighbor count, or regularization strength.
  • Confusion matrices revealed that no false positives or false negatives were made by any classifier, reinforcing the trustworthiness of the models on this dataset.

4.3 Conclusions¶

This study demonstrates that with well-engineered features, particularly the integration of textual sentiment analysis, machine learning models can predict refund requests with exceptional accuracy. Sentiment serves not only as a predictive feature but also enhances interpretability for business stakeholders. The models developed here can be readily integrated into customer service workflows to automate refund flagging, enabling faster resolution and improved customer satisfaction.

However, perfect accuracy should be interpreted with caution. In real-world settings, data may be noisier, feedback inconsistent, and behavior patterns more nuanced. Future work should include external validation, deployment testing, and possibly deep learning approaches for dynamic feedback analysis. Overall, this project illustrates the powerful synergy between structured ML pipelines and human sentiment, offering valuable insights for data-driven e-commerce optimization.
